Climate Moisture Index

26 November 2021


Introduction

The climate moisture index (CMI) quantifies the relationship between climate and vegetation by tracking moisture and temperature in forests to predict how well forests will grow. The following documents provide a description of two CMI datasets that were used for the Pan-Boreal Assessment (PBA) and Northwest Boreal (NWB) projects:

  • [Metadata for the NWB project’(docs/cmi_nwb.md)
  • [Metadata for the PBA project’(docs/cmi_pba.md)

A more recent version of the CMI dataset has been made available by Adaptwest:

In the current markdown document, we compare two approaches to calculating CMI, the first using the original method of Hargreaves and the second the revised version of Willmott and Feddema (1992) recommended by… First, we load the libraries that we will be using, read the boundary shapefile, and buffer it by 100km.

library(sf)
library(raster)
library(tidyverse)
library(tmap)
library(fasterize)
tmap_mode("view")
opts <- tmap_options(basemaps = c(Map="Esri.NatGeoWorldMap", OSM="OpenStreetMap.Mapnik", Imagery="Esri.WorldImagery"))
aea <- "+proj=aea +lat_0=45 +lon_0=-126 +lat_1=50 +lat_2=58.5 +x_0=1000000 +y_0=0 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs"
bnd <- st_read("data/kdtt.gpkg","bnd",quiet=T)
bnd100 <- st_buffer(bnd, 100000) %>%
    mutate(one=1)
r100 <- raster(bnd100, res=1000)
bnd100r <- fasterize(bnd100, r100, field="one")


CMI - original method

To illustrate the original method, we downloaded the most recent set of normal and projected bioclimatic maps for North America (CMIP6 scenarios) at a resolution 1-km2 from AdaptWest. Here, we select the 1970-2000 normal CMI map, clip it to the buffered boundary, and display it.

r <- raster('../../gisdata/north_america/climate/Normal_1971-2000_bioclim/Normal_1971_2000_CMI.tif')
tmp <- st_transform(bnd100, crs=crs(r)) # project to global raster (faster)
rc <- crop(r, tmp)
rcm <- mask(rc, tmp)
cmi_org <- projectRaster(from=rcm, to=bnd100r)

CMI distribution

Equal intervals

tm_shape(cmi_org) + tm_raster(n=10, palette="RdYlBu", style="equal", alpha=1, title = "CMI") +
    tm_shape(bnd) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="black") +
    tm_shape(bnd100) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="blue")


Quantile intervals

tm_shape(cmi_org) + tm_raster(n=10, palette="RdYlBu", style="quantile", alpha=1, title = "CMI") +
    tm_shape(bnd) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="black") +
    tm_shape(bnd100) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="blue")


CMI - revised method

The climatic moisture index (CMI) was used extensively by Thornthwaite et al. (2954?) is examined, and a modified version of the index is proposed (Ouellet Dallaire et al. (2019)). Arbitrary limits combined with its dimensionless property, make the original index difficult to interpret. The refined version also is dimensionless, but the limits have been recast so that \(-1 \le CMI \le 1\). Wet climates have positive values of CMI, while dry climates are negative, and the index is symmetric about zero.

Here, we generate the climate moisture index (CMI) for 1970-2000 for the boreal cordillera ecozone. We calculate CMI using the equation provided by Willmott and Feddema (Willmott and Feddema (1992)) using mean annual potential evapotranspiration from the Global-PET datasets (Zomer et al 2008, Trabucco and Zomer 2009) and mean annual precipitation from WorldClim (Hijmans et al 2005).

Alternatively, we could use the datasets from AdapWest: https://adaptwest.databasin.org/pages/adaptwest-climatena/

Calculate mean annual potential evapotranspiration 1970-2000

https://cgiarcsi.community/2019/01/24/global-aridity-index-and-potential-evapotranspiration-climate-database-v2/

pet <- raster('../../gisdata/global/climate/global-PET/et0_yr/et0_yr.tif')
bnd100_xy <- st_transform(bnd100, 4326) # project to NA raster (faster)
pet <- crop(pet, bnd100_xy)
pet <- mask(pet, bnd100_xy)
pet <- projectRaster(from=pet, to=bnd100r, method='ngb')

Alternatively, we could create mean annual PET from monthly grids:

# This code block is not run
ets <- stack()
for (i in 1:12) {
    if (i<10) {
        p <- raster(paste0('../../gisdata/global/climate/global-PET/et0_month/et0_0',i,'.tif'))
    } else {
        p <- raster(paste0('../../gisdata/global/climate/global-PET/et0_month/et0_',i,'.tif'))
    }
    ets <- stack(ets, p)
}
ets <- crop(ets, bnd100_xy)
ets <- mask(ets, bnd100_xy)
ets <- projectRaster(from=ets, to=bnd100r, method='ngb')
et_sum <- sum(ets)

Calculate mean annual precipitation 1970-2000

https://worldclim.org/data/worldclim21.html

ps <- stack()
for (i in 1:12) {
    if (i<10) {
        p <- raster(paste0('../../gisdata/global/climate/worldclim/wc2.1_30s_prec_0',i,'.tif'))
    } else {
        p <- raster(paste0('../../gisdata/global/climate/worldclim/wc2.1_30s_prec_',i,'.tif'))
    }
    ps <- stack(ps, p)
}
ps <- crop(ps, bnd100_xy)
ps <- mask(ps, bnd100_xy)
ps <- projectRaster(from=ps, to=bnd100r, method='ngb')
p <- sum(ps)

Calculate CMI

Values range from -1 to +1, with negative values indicating dry conditions and positivite values wet conditions.

rc <- function(p,pet) {
  ifelse(p<pet, (p/pet)-1, 1-(pet/p))
}
cmi_rev <- overlay(p, pet, fun=rc)

CMI distribution

Equal intervals

tm_shape(cmi_rev) + tm_raster(n=10, palette="RdYlBu", style="equal", alpha=1, title = "CMI") +
    tm_shape(bnd) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="black") +
    tm_shape(bnd100) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="blue")


Quantile intervals

tm_shape(cmi_rev) + tm_raster(n=10, palette="RdYlBu", style="quantile", alpha=1, title = "CMI") +
    tm_shape(bnd) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="black") +
    tm_shape(bnd100) + tm_borders(lwd=1, col="blue")
